docs.abstract: The former “Grey’s Anatomy” star is making his Broadway debut in “Take Me Out.” For that, he said, “I needed to go into a very unknown place.”
docs.snippet: The former “Grey’s Anatomy” star is making his Broadway debut in “Take Me Out.” For that, he said, “I needed to go into a very unknown place.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Jesse Williams will be the first tell you — certainly, he was the first to tell me — that he has no formal theater training and little practice. There’s an Edward Albee play in the hazy past and a one-act opposite Zosia Mamet. That’s pretty much it.

headline.main: So Long, Medical Scrubs. Jesse Williams Is Ready to Play Ball.

docs.abstract: The museum has a new logo and mantra as its director, Kaywin Feldman, moves to diversify the collection and the staff.
docs.snippet: The museum has a new logo and mantra as its director, Kaywin Feldman, moves to diversify the collection and the staff.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the doors reopen at the National Gallery of Art on Friday, visitors may be surprised by new changes to this Washington museum’s look. Some 20 clashing typefaces and confusing signage have been gradually disappearing from the building, replaced by a new logo visible inside and out, and a new mantra — “Of the nation and for all the people”— that will appear on its website and be shared with staff. The museum says this vision statement, developed through meetings with employees, symbolizes a renewed commitment to diversity, inclusion and excellence.

headline.main: National Gallery of Art Reopens With a New Vision: ‘For All the People’
headline.print_headline: A Vision and Rebirth for the 21st Century

docs.abstract: A variety of events have gone digital this year — and they’re joined by the marquee Global Pride livestream.
docs.snippet: A variety of events have gone digital this year — and they’re joined by the marquee Global Pride livestream.
docs.lead_paragraph: If you’re feeling conflicted about how to celebrate Pride this year, you’re hardly alone. Three months after the coronavirus pandemic turned the world on its head, America has been rocked by coast-to-coast protests inspired by George Floyd, whose death has led millions to cry out for an end to police brutality — and an end to police departments generally.

docs.abstract: With newfound momentum on social justice causes, players around the league have many opinions on what comes next. But most agree that the N.F.L. must recognize Colin Kaepernick.
docs.snippet: With newfound momentum on social justice causes, players around the league have many opinions on what comes next. But most agree that the N.F.L. must recognize Colin Kaepernick.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the wake of the killing of George Floyd in Minneapolis, the N.F.L., a league that has wrestled with racial issues for years, has shown unusual unity. Players, coaches, league officials and owners have expressed sadness, remorse and a commitment to seek solutions to police violence against African-American people and other forms of social injustice.

headline.main: The N.F.L. Embraces Progressive Action, but Not Yet Kaepernick
headline.print_headline: N.F.L. Embraces Calls for Justice, but Not Yet Kaepernick

docs.lead_paragraph: Harvard University’s next president will be Lawrence S.
